decisions:
  - Kept the app in JavaScript/JSX, used HashRouter, and centered the UI around a mobile-first shell with CSS modules plus global theme tokens.
  - Implemented a 69-card curated dataset with lesson metadata, quick-reference groupings, localStorage-backed study state, and a 5-box Leitner scheduler with delayed in-session requeue on Again.
  - Used markdown raw imports as the lesson source of truth, mapped stable section anchors from lesson metadata, and auto-marked section progress via IntersectionObserver when supported.
  - Added a custom manifest, service worker, generated PNG icon set, and install/update banner flow so the app is installable and can reload offline after an initial successful online visit.
evidence:
  - npm test -> PASS (5 test files, 15 tests passed)
  - npm run build -> PASS (Vite production build completed successfully)
  - npm run lint -> PASS (ESLint completed with no errors)
  - git commit -> PASS (feat: complete birth-prep study app)
open_risks:
  - Section completion depends on IntersectionObserver; unsupported browsers still read lessons normally but will not auto-mark section progress.
  - The flashcard corpus is manually curated from the two markdown lessons, so future lesson edits must keep cards and section metadata in sync by hand.
  - The service worker precaches shell assets and caches built assets at runtime, so offline reload still assumes at least one successful online visit first.
summary: Implemented the complete Birth Prep Study app described in plan.md: replaced the Vite starter with a mobile-first routed React PWA, added the full bilingual prenatal flashcard dataset and spaced repetition logic, wired persistent theme/study/lesson progress state, built the dashboard/lesson/study/quick-reference pages and shared components, generated install icons and service-worker support, removed starter assets, verified lint/tests/build, and committed the result at the recorded head SHA.
